		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Intellivision's CP1610 CPU</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />You may think it's strange that the CP1610 doesn't have an OR instruction, but remember the 6502 doesn't have a NOT instruction (XOR #$FF notwithstanding).<br /><br />Also, decles are nothing to worry about.  The CP1610 is fully capable of using 16-bit words (and is even more efficient in some operations when it can do so), and in fact the only reason they used 10-bit wide ROMs back in those days was to keep costs down.  The 10-bit ROMs in the original games feed logical zero to the upper 6 bits to accommodate the 16-bit bus.

		

